incredible focuses. Thanks, Michael. Thank you. Michael, before we go, I want to ask you

01:03:49.199 --> 01:03:55.679
about some of the things that you're working on and things we should be keeping an eye on

01:03:55.679 --> 01:04:00.159
or checking out as well. Yeah, that's a great question. I should have brought this up

01:04:00.159 --> 01:04:10.399
early. So I'm working with Julia Silgay and Isabel Zimmerman on ModelOps. So this is like,

01:04:10.399 --> 01:04:15.600
how can we make it really easy to go from a trained model to something you're able to serve

01:04:15.679 --> 01:04:21.840
so people can actually interact with or a service can use it, say, on a platform?

01:04:23.600 --> 01:04:29.760
And so that's been really exciting to see. A lot of the Tidy Models is focused on making it easy

01:04:29.760 --> 01:04:38.320
to train models and do all that. And then that last step or mile, which is getting it off your

01:04:38.320 --> 01:04:47.600
computer onto somewhere else and running as, say, like a web application. So I've been really

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:54.560
excited about that. And then I would say just working on Python tools in general, I've been

01:04:54.560 --> 01:05:03.520
really excited to almost like, I love the insights that people in the Tidyverse have. So to almost

01:05:03.520 --> 01:05:10.239
think about what's some of the magic that they've captured that we can bring into Python

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:16.719
to make data science a delight. And the one thing I'll say there is data science tools

01:05:16.719 --> 01:05:21.280
in Python are really interesting because I think, in general, the engineering tools in Python are

01:05:21.280 --> 01:05:28.560
incredible. So a lot of the pieces people in the Tidyverse had to build out, the foundational

01:05:28.560 --> 01:05:37.679
pieces are there. I think it's just the Tidyverse API and the high-level flow would bring so much. So

01:05:39.679 --> 01:05:42.320
yeah, super excited to work on that type of stuff.

01:05:44.800 --> 01:05:48.560
That's great. Thank you so much, Michael. I see Tatsu was sharing a few links

01:05:49.199 --> 01:05:55.120
in the chat for us to check out as well. But thank you all so much for joining today and for

01:05:55.120 --> 01:06:02.320
all the great questions too. Hopefully see you all back next week as well. But Michael,

01:06:02.320 --> 01:06:08.000
a huge thank you to you for filling in here last minute as well. Really appreciate you

01:06:08.719 --> 01:06:13.760
sharing your experience with us too. We haven't got a chance to talk at our studio too.

01:06:17.280 --> 01:06:20.399
No, thanks for the opportunity. I think it's super great having a bunch of people

01:06:21.040 --> 01:06:25.520
in a room just talking about the weird corners of data science.

01:06:27.199 --> 01:06:31.120
It's awesome. Thank you so much, Michael. Have a great rest of the day, everybody.

